{
  "doc_id": "8626",
  "text": "In all samples, 2-vinyl-4H-1,2-dithiin exhibited the highest content, followed by 3-vinyl-4H-1,2-dithiin. This indicated that these components were the major degradation product of allicin during frying. Vinyl dithiins have been reported as isomeric cyclic organosulfides. and are major components in distilled garlic oil [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . 2-Vinyl-4H-1,2-dithiin is the major vinyl dithiin, while 3-vinyl-4H-1,2-dithiin is a minor component, in agreement with our results. Vinyl dithiins might be derived from the thermal degradation of allicin or the interaction of degradation products of nonvolatile flavor precursors in garlic [CITATION_3] . Furthermore, allicin, when extracted by nonpolar organic solvents (mostly hexane) at slightly elevated temperatures, has been reported to transform into vinyl dithiins-as major components [CITATION_4] .",
